WEBVTT

00:00.898 --> 00:07.866
As we move from the gathering to listening, our scripture reading today is from the book of Colossians, chapter one verses 21 to 27.

00:10.609 --> 00:16.015
Once, you were alienated from God and were enemies in your minds because of your evil behavior.

00:17.296 --> 00:27.547
But now he has reconciled you by Christ's physical body through death to present you holy in his sight without blemish and free from accusation.

00:28.468 --> 00:29.970
If you continue in your faith,

00:30.338 --> 00:34.784
established and firm, and do not move from the hope held out in the gospel.

00:36.306 --> 00:44.057
This is the gospel that you heard, and that has been proclaimed to every creature under heaven, and of which I, Paul, have become a servant.

00:45.278 --> 00:56.914
Now, I rejoice in what I am suffering for you, and I fill up in my flesh what is still lacking in regard to Christ's afflictions for the sake of his body, which is the church.

00:57.954 --> 01:10.767
I've become its servant by the commission God gave me to present to you the word of God in its fullness, the mystery that has been kept hidden for ages and generations, but has now disclosed to the Lord's people.

01:12.029 --> 01:21.078
To them, God has chosen to make known among the Gentiles the glorious riches of this mystery, which is Christ in you, the hope of glory.

01:22.139 --> 01:23.260
This is the word of the Lord.

01:24.001 --> 01:24.882
Thanks be to God.

01:29.602 --> 01:30.263
Thank you, Fred.

01:31.144 --> 01:31.745
More in church.

01:33.368 --> 01:35.030
Good to see you all today.

01:35.070 --> 01:40.899
Special shout out to all you out in the new and improved smoking area under the tent.

01:41.280 --> 01:42.061
Glad you're here.

01:42.101 --> 01:47.590
And we made it to October, which is crazy, huh?

01:47.610 --> 01:51.576
And by the way, isn't October a strange name for the 10th month of the year?

01:54.300 --> 01:55.762
Feels like it should be the 8th.

02:03.362 --> 02:07.048
That clears that up, doesn't it?

02:07.068 --> 02:08.070
Thank you, Bradley.

02:08.110 --> 02:12.057
And here we go.

02:13.920 --> 02:23.877
Last week, if you're with us, we kicked off our Fall Vision series, which we're calling the whole gospel, a both-and-faith in an either-or world.

02:24.638 --> 02:29.106
And the reason that we're doing this series is because if Antioch is your church,

02:29.218 --> 02:34.525
then I want you to understand who we are and what we're all about as a community.

02:35.066 --> 02:41.615
I want you to be an active participant, not a passive spectator in the life of this church.

02:41.655 --> 02:49.846
And in order for that to happen, I think it's gonna be really helpful for you to have a firm grasp on our mission and our vision that we believe God has given us.

02:50.027 --> 02:53.491
And so I wanna do a little bit of recap just to catch us all up.

02:54.372 --> 02:58.418
Last week I introduced to you a shape called the Mandorla.

02:58.530 --> 03:00.052
And it means almond.

03:00.593 --> 03:08.186
And the idea is that this shape is created in a Venn diagram when two circles overlap.

03:08.787 --> 03:17.601
Or as we said, in other words, it's the new reality that emerges when two things that were separated are brought together.

03:19.364 --> 03:25.554
So this is why the mandorla has been so frequently used in Christian art throughout the centuries.

03:25.634 --> 03:35.171
It helps communicate so much of what we believe as followers of Christ that requires us to hold two truths at the same time.

03:35.691 --> 03:37.715
Meaning God is both three and one.

03:37.855 --> 03:40.059
Jesus is both human and divine.

03:40.139 --> 03:43.745
The kingdom of God is already and not yet.

03:43.846 --> 03:47.993
The mandorola helps us kind of capture some of that tension.

03:48.514 --> 03:51.058
And so last week I showed you this chart.

03:51.618 --> 03:56.588
And which is one of the ways I found helpful to explain kind of what our church is all about.

03:56.608 --> 04:07.890
And the idea is that if Antioch's can be faithful to our vision and mission, then we're going to kind of be a mandorla-shaped church that doesn't fit very nicely in any of the categories.

04:08.226 --> 04:14.953
What I proposed is that there's kind of two major streams in American Protestant Christianity at the moment.

04:15.133 --> 04:19.037
And on the left, you have what you might call theological liberalism.

04:19.538 --> 04:22.962
And on the right, what you might call biblical fundamentalism.

04:23.602 --> 04:30.089
And each of these sides tends to emphasize or focus on different aspects of Christian faith and practice.

04:30.229 --> 04:34.834
Now, I still think this is a really helpful chart in paradigm, but

04:34.978 --> 04:48.639
This last week, as I've thought about it more and reflected and had several meaningful conversations, I don't think that liberalism and fundamentalism are actually the clearest or most accurate labels for what we're talking about here.

04:48.799 --> 05:01.138
And so, I want to tell you why, with this caveat, I'm guessing that probably about 50% of you will not care about what I'm about to say, okay?

05:01.282 --> 05:09.837
If you're not into geeking out about the nuanced disparities between the various streams of North American Protestantism, that's okay.

05:09.857 --> 05:11.179
All right, you don't need to.

05:11.199 --> 05:17.810
I don't blame you, take the next five minutes, check your fantasy football team, and I'll call you back in a moment.

05:17.858 --> 05:25.951
For those of you that are interested in this stuff, let me tell you quickly why I don't think liberalism or fundamentalism are the best labels.

05:26.392 --> 05:37.970
The first has to do with liberalism, obviously, is a word in our culture that is predominantly, if not exclusively, used in a political context.

05:38.242 --> 05:39.744
We're not talking about politics.

05:39.764 --> 05:41.646
We're trying to talk about theology here.

05:42.087 --> 05:44.730
And so I don't think liberalism actually is that helpful.

05:45.070 --> 05:51.098
And on the other side, fundamentalism, I also think no longer means what it once meant.

05:51.659 --> 05:59.869
It once had to do with a basic set of beliefs or fundamentals that a certain group of Christians would hold.

06:00.229 --> 06:07.378
And I think now what it really means is not so much what you believe, but how you believe what you believe.

06:07.938 --> 06:08.739
Okay.

06:08.759 --> 06:18.277
And so there's an author by the name of Dan White Jr. who lists seven marks of fundamentalism that can actually apply to someone of any persuasion or ideology.

06:18.337 --> 06:19.539
I think this is fascinating.

06:20.000 --> 06:30.258
He says, absolutism and belief, self-righteous in spirit, combative in dialogue, us versus them in orientation, demonizing other groups,

06:30.306 --> 06:37.696
political policing ideological borders and using shame to control or ostracize.

06:37.756 --> 06:46.387
And so what's fascinating about this is that we now live in a world where there are fundamentalists both on the right and the left of every issue, right?

06:47.309 --> 06:51.674
You can be a fundamentalist conservative or fundamentalist liberal or anything else.

06:51.735 --> 06:55.740
And so that's not really what we're trying to talk about here either, so it's not helpful.

06:55.760 --> 06:57.362
So back to our chart.

06:57.634 --> 07:04.462
I want to modify our headings from fundamentalism and liberalism to evangelical and mainline.

07:04.823 --> 07:14.194
Now, these aren't perfect words either, but I think they are clearer and more accurate for describing the two dominant streams of Protestant Christianity in the West.

07:14.234 --> 07:17.818
And so these words just need a little bit of context real quickly.

07:17.838 --> 07:20.502
Mainline doesn't mean mainstream.

07:21.122 --> 07:27.410
Mainline refers primarily to those churches and organizations that are affiliated with the historic

07:27.810 --> 07:30.976
Protestant denominations of Christianity.

07:31.477 --> 07:37.808
So for the most part it's Lutherans, Methodists, Presbyterians, Episcopalians, Church of Christ.

07:38.710 --> 07:45.202
These are denominations that typically have been around a long time and for the most part when you're driving through

07:45.410 --> 07:53.520
an average American city, these are the church buildings that are old and big and usually begin with something first, right?

07:53.560 --> 07:57.004
This is true in most cities and including bend.

07:57.505 --> 08:11.442
And so, again, over simplification, overgeneralization, but in general, mainline Protestant churches tend to be more liberal in their theology and would be characterized more by the left side of our chart than the right.

08:11.778 --> 08:21.477
And then on the other side, we have evangelicalism, which obviously is also a word that has lots of baggage and political connotations these days, but I still think it's a helpful word.

08:22.178 --> 08:28.370
And evangelicalism, just like mainline, is diverse and not all churches look alike, but

08:28.546 --> 08:29.990
There are some common threads.

08:30.271 --> 08:41.381
First would be a very high view of the authority and inspiration of Scripture and the emphasis on the need for personal conversion and a relationship with God.

08:41.902 --> 08:44.690
And so most evangelical churches

08:45.282 --> 08:58.094
or I should say most like non-denominational churches would fall into the evangelical category along with most Baptist churches, Pentecostal, Charismatic, that sort of thing.

08:58.175 --> 09:08.665
So Southern Baptist, Calvary Chapel, Four Square, Assembly of God, Hillsong, all of those and others kind of fit into this evangelical category.

09:09.265 --> 09:14.130
So mainline evangelical and of course you have all sorts

09:14.306 --> 09:18.910
of churches and organizations that don't fit nicely into either camp.

09:18.930 --> 09:27.739
The historically black church in America, for example, doesn't fit nicely on here and really neither do like the Mennonites or other Anabaptist groups.

09:28.179 --> 09:33.184
And then of course you have tons of groups that do live somewhere in that space, right?

09:34.165 --> 09:40.070
Mainline Protestant churches that are more evangelical in their theology and vice versa.

09:40.130 --> 09:44.274
And so it's not perfect, but I think it helps get us there.

09:44.418 --> 09:54.815
So, okay, all of you that blacked out for the last five minutes, hopefully your roster set, you're looking good, welcome back, and we'll keep going.

09:55.356 --> 10:01.266
As I told you last week here at Antioch, our question is, what if we didn't have to choose one side or the other?

10:01.922 --> 10:08.171
What if we took a both and approach to our faith rather than either or?

10:08.211 --> 10:25.255
Rather than just a mainline or an evangelical, a liberal or a conservative gospel, one half of it, what if we were able to embrace and receive and practice and proclaim the whole gospel?

10:25.375 --> 10:26.877
What would that look like?

10:26.937 --> 10:30.642
That's what this series is about.

10:30.786 --> 10:37.653
Last thing by way of recap, a both and approach is not about a mushy middle, right?

10:38.113 --> 10:40.255
It's a radical third way.

10:40.976 --> 10:45.561
The goal isn't centrism or neutrality on every single issue.

10:46.461 --> 10:55.390
There will be plenty of times when faithfulness to Jesus requires us to hold a strong, hard position.

10:56.912 --> 10:59.314
Not every issue has two sides, but

10:59.554 --> 11:02.278
Taking a position is not the same thing as taking a side.

11:03.340 --> 11:14.396
Okay, so Jesus isn't neutral, but he is impartial, which is why for us, blue and orange don't make brown, blue and orange make gold, something all together separate.

11:14.857 --> 11:16.860
Okay, so that's the recap.

11:17.000 --> 11:23.970
This morning we move in to kind of our first specific in the series and it is the question of what is the gospel?

11:24.772 --> 11:26.354
What is the gospel?

11:26.530 --> 11:32.204
The passage of Fred read for us this morning from Colossians 1 picks right up where we left off last week.

11:33.046 --> 11:38.118
And if you remember Colossians 1 really is kind of a foundational text for us as a community.

11:38.178 --> 11:42.930
It's where we get our vision statement, the reconciliation of all things.

11:42.978 --> 11:54.455
And so Paul, the Apostle Paul is writing a letter to the church in Colossae, and he is going off in chapter one about the holistic nature of Christ's redemptive work on the cross.

11:54.535 --> 12:00.745
He says that through Jesus, God is reconciling or restoring all things to himself.

12:01.306 --> 12:05.492
Or in other words, all that God has made, God is now making new.

12:05.512 --> 12:12.242
And then in verse 23, where we were today, Paul concludes this section, he sums it up by saying,

12:12.514 --> 12:14.016
This is the gospel.

12:14.878 --> 12:24.193
This is the gospel that you heard and that has been proclaimed to every creature under heaven and of which I, Paul, have become a servant.

12:25.755 --> 12:32.546
Okay, so after going off about the reconciliation of all things, Paul wraps it all up by saying, this is the gospel.

12:33.247 --> 12:35.871
Everything I just told you, that's the gospel.

12:36.632 --> 12:40.178
And he says that this gospel's been proclaimed to every creature on earth,

12:40.994 --> 12:46.369
And this is the gospel to which he has given his life and become its servant.

12:47.111 --> 12:51.282
So whatever the gospel is to Paul is a very, very big deal.

12:51.874 --> 13:21.330
Now the word gospel is one we're familiar with it's used 76 times in the New Testament and the Greek it's you on jelly on which means good news of great joy and so today when we hear the word gospel we typically associate it with religion or spirituality but originally gospel was a journalistic term usually applied to political situations and so in the Greco-Roman world a gospel was a

13:21.474 --> 13:28.171
announcement breaking the news of something that had happened that would be good news for the hearers.

13:29.073 --> 13:35.730
So for example, you're probably familiar with the traditional story about where the modern marathon comes from.

13:36.098 --> 13:43.692
490 years before the time of Christ, the Persian Empire is invading this little town in Greece called Marathon.

13:44.072 --> 13:54.411
And everyone thinks that the Persians are just going to wipe it out, no problem, but somehow against the odds, the Greek soldiers were able to fend off the Persians and the city was saved.

13:55.092 --> 14:00.402
So this is a really big deal and changes the whole landscape of the conflict.

14:00.482 --> 14:06.851
And so the Greeks need to get message from marathon to Athens that they have won the battle.

14:07.351 --> 14:16.704
So they find a messenger to run from marathon to Athens and to announce that they have won the battle.

14:16.804 --> 14:20.790
Anybody want to take a guess how far it is from marathon to Athens?

14:21.551 --> 14:22.091
Anybody know?

14:22.111 --> 14:25.957
26.2 miles, exactly.

14:26.658 --> 14:29.842
By the way, you know how you can tell if somebody's run a marathon?

14:30.850 --> 14:31.771
Don't worry, they'll tell you.

14:32.693 --> 14:32.873
So.

14:37.300 --> 14:43.089
Anyways, the soldier runs the 26.2 miles from Marathon to Athens.

14:43.149 --> 14:48.778
And when he gets there, he goes out and he announces the good news, the gospel.

14:49.158 --> 14:50.701
We have one.

14:51.422 --> 14:52.183
And then what happens?

14:53.285 --> 14:53.806
He dies.

14:54.166 --> 14:55.849
He drops dead.

14:56.169 --> 14:59.314
All right, the very first guy to run a marathon dies.

14:59.970 --> 15:01.912
And then later on, someone's like, you know what?

15:01.932 --> 15:03.014
We should make this a thing.

15:05.096 --> 15:06.358
Like, let's all get together.

15:06.418 --> 15:08.541
We'll put on our short shorts.

15:09.702 --> 15:12.546
We'll run 26 miles and see if we die.

15:12.566 --> 15:15.529
I don't know who thought that was a good idea.

15:15.750 --> 15:22.057
But the message that this runner carried was a gospel.

15:22.518 --> 15:29.106
And the name of that runner or herald was an evangelist, a bearer of good news that would bring

15:29.218 --> 15:29.799
great joy.

15:29.819 --> 15:32.664
And so gospel wasn't originally a religious word.

15:33.084 --> 15:37.992
It was a journalistic word about a political or historical announcement.

15:39.214 --> 15:47.969
Okay, so for over 2000 years now, Christians have recognized that at the center of our faith is a gospel.

15:49.892 --> 15:53.618
The good news about something that has happened

15:54.402 --> 16:00.268
We understand all Christians, wherever you are, that at the center of Christian faith isn't good advice.

16:00.288 --> 16:04.552
That here's the things you need to do in order to be made right with God.

16:05.092 --> 16:07.595
At the center of the Christian faith is good news.

16:08.115 --> 16:11.799
Here's the thing that God has done to bring us close to Him.

16:12.840 --> 16:16.844
So all Christians agree that at the center of Christianity is the gospel.

16:18.105 --> 16:23.570
But I don't think all Christians agree when it comes to what is that gospel.

16:24.418 --> 16:41.682
Okay, so if we plug the gospel into our mainline evangelical chart, then we might say that mainline Christianity tends to emphasize the gospel of Jesus while evangelical Christianity tends to emphasize the gospel about Jesus.

16:42.002 --> 16:45.167
Again, generalizations, but I think it's helpful.

16:45.187 --> 16:47.029
Let me break these down real quick.

16:47.109 --> 16:53.298
When I say the gospel of Jesus, I'm talking about the gospel that Jesus himself preached.

16:53.858 --> 17:00.947
Jesus was a preacher, a teacher, and he had a gospel message that he proclaimed.

17:01.367 --> 17:02.549
I'll show you a couple places.

17:03.269 --> 17:07.535
In Mark's gospel, here's how Jesus launches his public ministry.

17:08.636 --> 17:23.474
After John was put in prison, Jesus went into Galilee proclaiming the good news of God, or the gospel of God, and it's this, the time has come, he said, the kingdom of God has come near, repent,

17:23.554 --> 17:26.238
and believe the good news or the gospel.

17:27.300 --> 17:38.536
So Jesus declares a message that to be good news of great joy and that message is summarized that the kingdom of God has come near.

17:39.938 --> 17:44.285
This is the gospel of Jesus, the gospel according to Jesus.

17:45.386 --> 17:47.029
One more example in Luke's gospel.

17:47.730 --> 17:53.458
The very first time Jesus stands up to give a sermon, he simply reads

17:53.634 --> 17:54.676
from the book of Isaiah.

17:55.898 --> 18:04.451
He says, the spirit of the Lord is on me because he has anointed me to proclaim good news or the gospel to the poor.

18:05.232 --> 18:15.969
He has sent me to proclaim freedom for the prisoners and recovery of sight for the blind and to set the oppressed free and to proclaim the year of the Lord's favor.

18:17.111 --> 18:21.938
And then Jesus sits down and says, today the scripture is fulfilled in your hearing.

18:23.234 --> 18:36.749
Okay, another example of the gospel according to Jesus that can be summarized, that the kingdom of God has come to earth and that that kingdom is going to be subversive.

18:37.350 --> 18:39.052
It's going to be disruptive.

18:39.732 --> 18:49.463
It's going to confront the status quo of who's in and who's out, who's weak, who's strong, who has the power, who's vulnerable.

18:50.484 --> 18:51.986
And so Jesus comes

18:52.130 --> 19:00.621
With this kingdom, he says it's gonna be good news to the poor because it's gonna overthrow empirical powers of violence and greed.

19:00.641 --> 19:07.431
He's gonna liberate the poor, alleviate suffering, administer justice and make peace on earth.

19:08.712 --> 19:10.475
That's the gospel of Jesus.

19:11.997 --> 19:19.326
And it tends to be how mainline Protestants think about the gospel of Christianity.

19:20.047 --> 19:21.970
Now in evangelical Christianity,

19:22.562 --> 19:33.778
There's typically less of a focus on the gospel of Jesus and more of a focus on the gospel about Jesus, meaning the gospel that Paul and the other apostles preached

19:34.082 --> 19:40.174
about who Jesus was, how he lived, what he did, and accomplished in his death and resurrection.

19:40.735 --> 19:51.595
And so this is really the view that the gospel contains the basic set of biblical truths that someone would need to believe in order to become a follower of Jesus.

19:52.176 --> 19:57.266
Now there's lots of ways you could try to unpack kind of the gospel about Jesus, one of the most

19:57.506 --> 20:01.310
prominent ones in evangelicalism is called Roman's Road.

20:01.651 --> 20:03.353
And some of you may be familiar with it.

20:03.773 --> 20:14.825
And it basically just uses the book of Romans and five specific verses that aren't just random verses but kind of are to be understood as a story that builds on itself.

20:15.266 --> 20:18.650
And so let's walk through these five verses of the Roman Road real quick.

20:19.130 --> 20:22.674
Number one, for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God.

20:23.298 --> 20:26.883
Number two, but God demonstrates his own love for us in this.

20:27.444 --> 20:29.908
While we were still sinners, Christ died for us.

20:30.729 --> 20:36.357
Number three, for the wages of sin is death, but the gift of God is eternal life in Christ Jesus our Lord.

20:36.397 --> 20:41.945
Number four, therefore there is now no condemnation for those who are in Christ Jesus.

20:42.566 --> 20:50.578
And number five, if you declare with your mouth Jesus is Lord and believe in your heart that God raised him from the dead, you will be saved.

20:51.042 --> 20:56.571
Okay, this is a very common way of talking about the gospel within evangelicalism.

20:57.353 --> 21:01.900
And it's straight from the scripture and it's good and it's true and it's beautiful.

21:03.363 --> 21:11.637
But a more mainline Christian would hear that and say, yeah, that's great, but that's not the gospel.

21:12.618 --> 21:14.802
That's maybe the plan for salvation.

21:16.354 --> 21:22.601
Don't you think that a follower of Jesus when they talk about the gospel should talk about the gospel that Jesus himself preached?

21:23.422 --> 21:25.925
Wouldn't that be a little bit more fitting?

21:25.965 --> 21:27.807
Like Jesus didn't do Romans' road.

21:28.788 --> 21:32.393
He announced the in-breaking of the kingdom of God.

21:34.395 --> 21:40.402
So, on the left you have the gospel of Jesus and on the right the gospel about Jesus.

21:40.802 --> 21:43.104
This isn't something I came up with, by the way.

21:43.224 --> 21:48.469
This is stuff that theologians and religious scholars have been observing for years.

21:49.290 --> 21:59.180
I think the first time I came across this specifically was about 20 years ago in a book called This Beautiful Mess by my friend and mentor Rick McKinley.

21:59.780 --> 22:05.566
And so let me just read you a paragraph real quick that sums up this whole problem.

22:06.226 --> 22:09.970
Sometimes it seems as though we find two gospels in the New Testament.

22:10.370 --> 22:12.815
The gospel of Jesus and the gospel about Jesus.

22:13.296 --> 22:21.692
The gospel of Jesus is usually taken to mean his announcement of the kingdom and the life he embodied in his loving actions towards the world.

22:22.414 --> 22:32.754
The gospel about Jesus refers to his atoning work on the cross and his resurrection through which we can receive the forgiveness of sin through our faith and repentance.

22:33.154 --> 22:36.260
The two gospels even correlate to a schism in the church.

22:36.721 --> 22:50.546
With more liberal churches living the gospel of Jesus and doing the good deeds of the kingdom, while more conservative churches preach the gospel about Jesus, focusing on the personal salvation he offers to those who put their faith in him.

22:51.308 --> 22:54.033
So that lays it out pretty clearly.

22:54.914 --> 22:56.978
So you might say, according to Rick,

22:57.634 --> 23:07.446
I could sum up the divide like this, that there's one version of the gospel that's all about the kingdom of God, and then there's another version of the gospel that's all about salvation.

23:09.108 --> 23:15.276
Okay, and like I said, lots of people, lots of pastors, theologians, biblical scholars have observed this stuff over the years.

23:15.816 --> 23:27.090
So if we took the thinking of someone like Timothy Keller, for example, and we applied it to this equation, then you might say that on the left, we have justice people.

23:27.650 --> 23:30.734
And on the right, we have justification people.

23:31.936 --> 23:49.578
Or one more example, if we took the thinking of Mark Sayers, the Australian pastor and thinker, then we might apply his work to this, and it would look like this, that the left wants the kingdom, but not the king, and the right wants the king, but not the kingdom.

23:51.280 --> 23:52.562
Very interesting.

23:53.890 --> 24:02.925
So here's the problem within Protestant Christianity, we have these two gospels and each of them on their own is incomplete.

24:05.669 --> 24:10.658
What we want and what we're after is the whole gospel.

24:11.880 --> 24:16.547
We don't want to choose one side or the other, we want the whole thing.

24:17.689 --> 24:20.594
And that's what we find in Colossians 1.

24:21.442 --> 24:28.833
As we saw last week, verses 15 through 20 have this very zoomed out big picture view of how Jesus is saving the world.

24:29.153 --> 24:34.041
And Paul says that in Christ, God is reconciling all things to himself.

24:34.121 --> 24:45.758
And then in verse 21, Paul zooms in and he focuses on how this message of reconciliation plays out in the lives of individual people.

24:46.860 --> 24:51.186
In verse 21, he says, once you were alienated from God,

24:51.362 --> 24:55.286
and you were enemies in your minds because of your evil behavior.

24:55.967 --> 25:08.399
But now he has reconciled you by Christ's physical body through death to present you wholly in his sight without blemish and free from accusation.

25:10.862 --> 25:13.284
Here's what I love about what Paul does here.

25:14.585 --> 25:19.090
Paul starts by talking about the reconciliation of all things.

25:19.842 --> 25:29.095
this huge limitless cosmic vision of the gospel that all God has made, He is now making new.

25:30.257 --> 25:41.933
And then Paul zooms in and speaks specifically within the reconciliation of all things, how God is reconciling humanity to Himself.

25:42.994 --> 25:48.562
Or in other words, if God is making all things new, we are part of all things.

25:50.050 --> 25:55.576
He is restoring all things to Himself, and that includes you.

25:55.636 --> 25:58.259
And that includes me.

25:58.459 --> 26:00.582
This is a much bigger gospel.

26:00.642 --> 26:04.045
This is not the kingdom of God versus salvation.

26:04.366 --> 26:07.549
This is not justice versus justification.

26:08.010 --> 26:09.551
This is both and.

26:09.992 --> 26:13.736
Jesus is saving the world and He wants to save you.

26:13.776 --> 26:19.122
That's the kind of gospel I can get excited about.

26:19.778 --> 26:23.562
That's the kind of church we believe God has called us to be.

26:24.443 --> 26:27.306
Not either or, but both and the whole thing.

26:27.406 --> 26:28.727
Good news for the poor.

26:29.188 --> 26:30.649
Good news for the oppressed.

26:30.729 --> 26:36.955
Good news for the broken and salvation for the lost, including you and including me.

26:38.277 --> 26:38.978
How does that work?

26:39.618 --> 26:40.459
We'll close with this.

26:41.320 --> 26:47.346
Paul says that once we were alienated from God and we lived as his enemies.

26:48.354 --> 26:52.079
Now that's a little bit offensive, if we're honest, right?

26:52.099 --> 27:02.914
And it may sound kind of like an extreme statement to make about you or me or any of us, but I think if we're honest, we all know what it feels like to be alienated from God.

27:04.617 --> 27:07.381
I love the way Wendell Berry talks about this.

27:07.461 --> 27:16.914
Wendell Berry is the farmer poet who's been called the sanest man in America, and he puts it like this, we all come from divorce.

27:17.570 --> 27:19.833
This is an age of divorce.

27:19.853 --> 27:26.042
Things that belong together have been taken apart, and you can't put it all back together again.

27:28.025 --> 27:29.907
Barry's not just talking about divorce and marriage.

27:30.769 --> 27:35.475
He's talking about the divorce of everything from everything, right?

27:35.976 --> 27:45.970
If you think about the state of the world, the state of our families, our churches, our cities, our nations, things that belong together have been pulled apart.

27:46.690 --> 27:50.856
As humans, we are divorced from the earth and the environment.

27:51.858 --> 27:59.128
As people, we're divorced from each other because of our race or class or politics or religion.

27:59.929 --> 28:01.592
We're divorced from ourselves.

28:02.012 --> 28:11.346
No thanks to our screens and our addiction, to stimulation and technology and our biggest problem of all is that we're divorced from God.

28:12.354 --> 28:16.899
We live in an age of divorce, things that belong together have been pulled apart.

28:17.200 --> 28:20.043
And Paul says, that's the state of humanity.

28:20.363 --> 28:21.585
That's the state of the world.

28:22.466 --> 28:31.977
But he says, now God is reconciling all things, including us back to himself.

28:32.217 --> 28:33.379
What's reconciliation?

28:34.700 --> 28:36.242
It's the opposite of divorce.

28:37.858 --> 28:42.323
It's when things that were separated are brought together.

28:43.184 --> 28:46.127
The holistic repair of severed relationships.

28:46.147 --> 28:54.656
And so the picture is even though we were unfaithful to God, we cheated on God, we left God, we abandoned God, we divorced God.

28:55.497 --> 28:58.580
In Christ, He has absorbed our sin.

29:00.963 --> 29:07.410
And He has given us a new name and a new family and a new identity.

29:08.066 --> 29:11.992
and a new destiny as his beloved people.

29:13.394 --> 29:27.995
And so the way Paul explains the significance of Christ's life, death, and resurrection is by starting with the fact that God is making all things new and then by reminding us that we are included in all things.

29:28.936 --> 29:30.899
It's not either or it's both and.

29:31.821 --> 29:35.506
So when we talk about being a church that's about the whole gospel, this is what we're talking about.

29:36.258 --> 29:47.211
believing and proclaiming a bigger and better gospel than the left-right divide could ever embody a gospel more glorious than the world could ever imagine.

29:48.092 --> 29:50.315
Paul says that he is a servant of this gospel.

29:50.375 --> 29:59.126
He's given his entire life to it, which may sound extreme, but the truth is all of us have given our lives to one gospel or another.

30:00.668 --> 30:05.714
And if we haven't become servants of the gospel of Jesus, then we are serving another gospel.

30:06.786 --> 30:16.902
The gospel of self, the gospel of America, the gospel of wealth, the gospel of comfort, or power, or control, or whatever it is.

30:19.867 --> 30:22.411
There's no gospel like the Christian gospel.

30:22.751 --> 30:24.374
There's no savior like Jesus.

30:26.677 --> 30:33.007
Let's be a church that gives ourself to this gospel that's good news for the whole world, including you and me.

30:33.608 --> 30:34.610
Amen.

